Row.Text: Chalcedonian Christianity refers to Christian denominations adhering to the christological definitions and ecclesiological resolutions of the Council of Chalcedon, or the Fourth Ecumencial Council of 451 A.D. Followers believe in the Definition of Chalcedon or dyophysitism that declares that Jesus Christ had two natures: wholly human and wholly divine. Chalcedonianism descends from the earlier Nicene Christianity. At conception Chalcedonianism was at schism with Non-Chalcedonian churches, following christological monophysitism or miaphysitism, many of these churches are considered Oriental Orthodoxy. Five major pentarchs: ecumencial patriarch (pope) of Rome, ecumencial patriarch of Constantinople (New Rome), and the three eastern patriarchs of Alexandria, Antioch, and Jerusalem; were pillars of the orthodox catholic Christendom. The patriarchs eventually became recognised as the Pentarchy of the Roman Empire's official church.

Catholic Christianity refers to all Christian denominations underneath the leadership of the bishop of Rome, the Pope, whose primary church is the Roman Catholic Church. Catholicism asserts that it is the one, holy, catholic, and apostolic church founded by Jesus Christ in his Great Comission. The Pope holds titles such as "vicar of Christ" and "successor to Saint Peter." Catholicism descends from Nicene and later Chalcedonian Christianity, holding the traditional dyophysitism christology. Catholicism obseverves several major sacraments, iconography, and reverance of saints.

The term "the chosen people" could refer to any sort of group - ethnic or religious, become "chosen" or patronize a certain deity. Historically there were many peoples that would become favored by entitites, examples include Germanic Saxons and their protector god Saxnot or Mongolic/Turkic peoples being chosen by Tengri.According to Abrahamic traditions, the Jews descend from the prophet Abraham and his covenant with God. Since the prophethood of Abraham, his descendants would undergo various events and turmoil in history, which would often see certain people rise to the status of prophet.

The Messiah or "annointed one" is a concept that originated in Jewish scriptures and later through Christianity and fictional literature the concept can be applied to an archetypical heroic figure that would lead people in a golden age. In ancient Jewish texts the concept of the messiah could apply to awaited and divinely guided leadership, in particular a person of the line of David. In Christianity Jesus of Nazareth is the Messiah or "Christ," unlike in previous Jewish texts, Jesus is viewed as the sole messiah and Son of God. In Islam the messianic figure could apply to Isa (Jesus) but other characters such as the Mahdavi are believed to be imminent and will usher in a golden age as well. In Manichaeism messiahs and buddhas are similar in nature, and prophets such as Mani are the continuation of prophecy. In Dharmic religions such as Hinduism and Buddhism the awaited avatar of Vishnu: Kalkin; and the awaited buddha: Maitraya; are characters that can be considered messiahs as they will appear during a world changing event.
